post_text:
An update for our junior high student athletes and participants of IESA sponsored events.

The IESA Board unanimously approved to cancel the regular season and IESA state series in the sports of boys and girls golf, boys baseball, girls softball, and boys and girls cross-country for the 2020-21 school year. There are no plans to try and reschedule the activities or conduct them later in the school year in part due to if and when high schools in Illinois play their contests. The IESA Board delayed any decision on girls basketball. The first day of girls basketball practice is scheduled for August 31. The Board will meet again in late August to make a decision regarding girls basketball. The Board did review and approve a plan submitted by the Speech Advisory Committee that allows schools to hold their own speech contest during the upcoming school year. Schools that participate in speech will receive information at a later date. No decisions regarding any other activities were made.
https://www.iesa.org/

A group of teachers and administration have begun the process of creating a plan to return to school in the fall. Working through the guidance provided last week by the Illinois State Board of Education, (ISBE), and Illinois Department of Public Health, (IDPH), we are looking to find the best way to teach, nourish, support, transport and empower our kids.

We are getting closer to making that happen but we need your partnership more than ever for our plan to be successful.

Below is a link to a survey that we need every family to complete so that we will have accurate information to further develop our plan.

The survey will be open through 8:00 AM, Monday, July 6, 2020.

Thank you again for your support as we work together to meet the needs with our learning community. Together we can and will succeed.

https://forms.gle/7fsG4XHzi1QqdGmV8

Teacher Appreciation Week starts on Monday!! Although we can’t shower our teachers and staff with the appreciation we normally show them, let’s make this week special - quarantine style 😉! post_text:
Dear Virginia CUSD 64 Learning Community,

Communication will be a key part of our transition to our remote learning plan starting next week. To facilitate communication from teachers to parents, we are in need of parent/guardian email addresses that can be linked with individual student accounts in Teacher Ease and School Messenger.

Please submit this information via one of the following methods:

1. Complete the google form https://forms.gle/ENhWtjamdfW29Zup9 listed on www.virginiacusd64.com website or posted on our Virginia CUSD 64 Facebook Page
2. Contact our school office at 217-452-3363. If no one is available to answer your phone call, we would ask that you leave a voicemail with the requested information (your name, your student(s) name and grade level).
3. Email your information (your name, your student(s) name and grade level) to mneathery@virginia64.com.

Please submit this information by April 1, 2020, to allow time for processing and updating our information systems.

We again thank you for your continued support.

LIFEGUARD TRAINING COURSE

PORTA Pool in Petersburg will conduct the American Red Cross Lifeguard Certification Training Course March 26 - 29. Trainees must be 15 years old by March 29 and must pass the pre-course swim. Classes will be 5:30 - 7:30 p.m. on Thursday, 3/26; 5:30 - 8:30 p.m. on Friday, 3/27; 8:30 a.m. - 5:30 p.m. on Saturday, 3/28; and 8:30 a.m. - 5:30 p.m. on Sunday, 3/29. Students must attend all class sessions. For more information and to pre-register, contact Rachel Frost, PORTA Pool Manager, 217/632-4745.

A child’s ability to read has a direct effect on their future success. Reading with your child helps to increase their vocabulary and improves their reading fluency and comprehension.

On March 2nd, we encourage EVERYONE to pick up a book and read to a child.

Whether it’s a beloved classic or something new and exciting, we encourage you to spread the joy of reading

For more information, visit NEA’s Read Across America site at www.readacrossamerica.org.

shared_text:
Ansar Shriners
February 18 at 10:32 AM ·

The Virginia CUSD #64 4th grade class went above and beyond this year breaking the record for their largest donation to date with $4032.71.
Since the 4th grade class stated this fundraiser in 1994, they have raised $55,000 for our amazing Shriners Hospitals for Children - St. Louis.

This year was especially special for us because Preston, a patient at our Shriners Hospitals for Children- St. Louis and our incredible patient ambassador was part of this years class and gave a challenge to his class - the student who raised the most money gets to design his new prosthetic. We can’t wait to see what they come up with!

Thank you for all your hard work and your amazing support of our Shriners Hospitals for Children and Shriners International

post_text:
DELAYED START for February 13th, 2020.

This is superintendent Gary DePatis. On Thursday, February 13th Virginia schools will utilize our late start option. This means that buses will run two hours later than normal and school will start two hours later than normal. Student drop off will begin at 9:30 AM as staff will not be available for supervision until that time. Classes will begin at 10 AM. There will be no breakfast served in the morning and lunches will be served as normal. There will be no pre-K classes in the morning and the afternoon pre-K class will attend as usual. Any students that attend outside of district in Jacksonville, Springfield or Petersburg Porta will not be going to school tomorrow. Dismissal at the end of the day will be the same 3:02 PM as normal. The late start schedule is available on the Virginia 64.com website.
